:::summary
Indian philosophy is one of the oldest and deepest philosophical traditions in the world, stretching back more than three thousand years to the Vedic hymns and the profound philosophical dialogues of the Upanishads. It encompasses a dazzling diversity of schools — the six orthodox Hindu *darśanas*, the heterodox traditions of Buddhism and Jainism, and the medieval Vedānta schools — unified by shared questions about the nature of the self (*ātman*), ultimate reality (*Brahman*), liberation (*moksha*), and right action (*dharma*). India produced some of the most sophisticated work in epistemology, logic, metaphysics, and philosophy of mind of any civilization, and its tradition remains a living force in world thought today.
